  "prompt": "My 10 yr old often does things he knows are wrong. Is this normal? It's not stuff when he's angry through impulse it's when he is calm",
  "response": "It's not uncommon for 10-year-old children to sometimes intentionally break rules or do things they know are wrong. This behavior can stem from various reasons:\n\n1. Testing boundaries\n- Children at this age are exploring independence\n- They want to understand limits and consequences\n\n2. Attention-seeking\n- Misbehavior can be a way to get parental attention\n- Even negative attention can feel rewarding\n\n3. Curiosity\n- Some children want to see what will happen\n- They're learning about cause and effect\n\n4. Lack of impulse control\n- Brain development is still in progress\n- Self-regulation skills are still developing\n\n5. Underlying emotional issues\n- Stress, anxiety, or feeling misunderstood\n- Possible need for more emotional support\n\nRecommended approaches:\n- Stay calm and consistent\n- Set clear expectations and consequences\n- Use logical consequences\n- Praise good behavior\n- Communicate openly\n- Listen to understand his perspective\n- Consider if there might be deeper issues\n\nIf the behavior seems persistent or concerning, consider:\n- Talking to his pediatrician\n- Consulting a child psychologist\n- Discussing with his school counselor\n\nRemember, this is a normal part of development, and patience and consistent guidance are key.",
